Reading Files

Solution 
# reading files

artist_top_hits <- read.csv("~/Downloads/artist_top_hits.csv") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

artist_albums <- read.csv("~/Downloads/artist_studio_albums.csv") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

artist_one_hits <- read.csv("~/Downloads/artist_number_one_hits.csv") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

artist_worth <- read.csv("~/Downloads/artist_net_worth.csv") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

artist_name <- read.csv("~/Downloads/artist_name.csv") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

artist_genre <- read.table("~/Downloads/artist_genre.txt", header = TRUE) %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()



Identifying and Removing Duplicated Artists

Solution 
# for the these data sets, 12 artists have duplicated rows appear more than once

# code that extracts artists who appear more than once in each data set

artist_name_duplicates <- data.frame(unique(artist_name$artist[duplicated(artist_name$artist)]))

artist_albums_duplicates <- data.frame(unique(artist_albums$artist[duplicated(artist_albums$artist)]))

artist_genre_duplicates <- data.frame(unique(artist_genre$artist[duplicated(artist_genre$artist)]))

artist_one_hits_duplicates <- data.frame(unique(artist_one_hits$artist[duplicated(artist_one_hits$artist)]))

artist_top_hits_duplicates <- data.frame(unique(artist_top_hits$artist[duplicated(artist_top_hits$artist)]))

artist_worth_duplicates <- data.frame(unique(artist_worth$artist[duplicated(artist_worth$artist)]))


# getting rid of rows to ensure artists only appear in one row in each dataset

artist_name <- artist_name[!duplicated(artist_name[c("artist")]), ]

artist_one_hits <- artist_one_hits[!duplicated(artist_one_hits[c("artist")]), ]

artist_top_hits <- artist_top_hits[!duplicated(artist_top_hits[c("artist")]), ]

artist_worth <- artist_worth[!duplicated(artist_worth[c("artist")]), ]

artist_albums <- artist_albums[!duplicated(artist_albums[c("artist")]), ]

artist_genre <- artist_genre[!duplicated(artist_genre[c("artist")]), ]



Merging Data Sets

Solution 
# merging all data into one data frame

merged_artist <- merge(artist_albums, artist_genre, by = "artist")
merged_artist <- merge(merged_artist, artist_name, by = "artist")
merged_artist <- merge(merged_artist, artist_one_hits, by = "artist")
merged_artist <- merge(merged_artist, artist_top_hits, by = "artist")
merged_artist <- merge(merged_artist, artist_worth, by = "artist")



Creating New Variables

Solution 
# creating age variable
merged_artist$age <- (2023 - merged_artist$birth_year)

# removing $ symbol from any value in the net worth column
merged_artist$net_worth_millions = gsub("\\$", "", merged_artist$net_worth_millions)

# creating net worth per studio album
merged_artist$net_worth_millions <- as.integer(merged_artist$net_worth_millions)

merged_artist$net_worth_per_album <- 
  round(merged_artist$net_worth_millions / merged_artist$studio_albums, digits = 2)

# renaming year column to hit_year
colnames(merged_artist)[colnames(merged_artist) == "year"] = "hit_year"

# creating age at biggest hit variable
merged_artist$hit_age <- merged_artist$hit_year - merged_artist$birth_year

Question 2

Which artists are above the mean of net worth per studio album?

Aolution 
# creating avg_worth variable
avg_worth <- round(mean(merged_artist$net_worth_per_album), digits = 2)

# finding artists who qualify as having an above average net worth
above_avg_artists <- merged_artist$net_worth_per_album > avg_worth

# creating data frame of these names
high_worth_artists <- data.frame(merged_artist[above_avg_artists, ]$artist)

rmarkdown::paged_table(high_worth_artists)


The above artists have a greater net worth per album than the average net worth of 32.42 million.



Question 3

Plotting net worth per studio album, "been around" variable, and genre

Solution 
library(ggplot2)

# creating scatter plot of net_worth_per_album compared to age, categorized by genre
age_album_plot <- ggplot(merged_artist, aes(x = net_worth_per_album, y = age, color = genre )) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "net worth per studio album",
       y = "artist band/age",
       title = "Relationship Between Net Worth, Age, and Music Genre") +
   theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue",
                                  linewidth = 0.5, linetype = "solid", 
                                  color = "darkblue")
  )

age_album_plot



Question 4

Examining the relationship between net worth and music popularity

Solution 
# creating scatter plot examining the relationship betweeen number of #1 hits and net worth

worth_hits_plot <- ggplot(merged_artist, aes(x = number_one_hits, y = net_worth_millions)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(y = "Overall Net Worth (in millions of Dollars)",
       x = "  Amount of Number One Hits ",
       title = "Relationship Between Net Worth and Number one Hits") +
   theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold")
  )

worth_hits_plot
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

In general, artists who have more number one hits generate a higher net worth for themselves
